Any enclosure of arable land by means of a hedge and a ditch, although outside the covert of the forest, was reckoned a purpresture, notwithstanding the fact that the Charter of the Forest permitted3 every free man ‘to make arable outside the covert in arable land.’ In all such cases the offender was amerced at the forest cyre. It should be noticed that a man might be liable for an assart and a purpresture with respect to the same piece of land. He might cut down a parcel of wood‚ reduce it to cultivation, and then enclose it with a hedge and a ditch. In this case there would be a single entry recording the facts on the eyre rolls, which might be found either

among the New Purprestures or the New Assarts.
